{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531879"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:20:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:20:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14635"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14635"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.06,0.63,0.05,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57564"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7328"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14635"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43023"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"2000"},{"type":"tags","id":"2287"},{"type":"tags","id":"3494"},{"type":"tags","id":"3637"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17888"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57564"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting travel vaccinations for an upcoming trip to South America in two weeks. She has been taking prednisolone for giant cell arteritis, initially at 30mg daily three months ago and tapering over the past two months to her current dose of 20mg daily. Her other medications include calcium/vitamin D supplements and alendronate. She has no other significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has mild cushingoid features.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vaccines is contraindicated in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Typhoid injectable vaccine","Tetanus booster","Yellow fever vaccine","Hepatitis B vaccine","Hepatitis A vaccine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is immunosuppressed due to high-dose corticosteroid therapy (prednisolone \u003Cstrong\u003E\u2265\u003C/strong\u003E20mg daily for \u003Cstrong\u003E\u2265\u003C/strong\u003E2 weeks). In immunosuppressed patients, live vaccines are contraindicated due to the risk of vaccine strain infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYellow fever vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E is a live attenuated vaccine and is therefore contraindicated in this patient. The risk of developing vaccine-associated disease outweighs the benefit in immunosuppressed individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E is an inactivated vaccine and is safe to administer to immunosuppressed patients. While the immune response may be suboptimal, there is no risk of vaccine strain infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETyphoid injectable vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E (Vi polysaccharide vaccine) is an inactivated vaccine and is safe in immunosuppression. Note that the oral typhoid vaccine is live and would be contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETetanus booster\u003C/strong\u003E contains toxoid and is an inactivated vaccine, making it safe for immunosuppressed patients. Maintaining tetanus immunity is particularly important in immunosuppressed individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E is a recombinant vaccine containing only surface antigen and is safe in immunosuppression, though multiple doses may be required to achieve adequate immunity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther live vaccines that would be contraindicated in this patient include measles-mumps-rubella (MMR), varicella, and the BCG (bacille Calmette\u2013Gu\u00e9rin) vaccine. Instead, inactivated or subunit vaccines should be used where available.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Live vaccines are contraindicated in immunosuppressed patients, including high-dose corticosteroids, due to risk of vaccine strain infection.","Pneumocystis jirovecii prophylaxis should be considered in patients on high-dose steroids for prolonged periods."],"references":["Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation (ATAGI). Australian Immunisation Handbook, Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care, Canberra, 2022, immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43023"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14635"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43023"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-26T19:49:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-26T19:50:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7328"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57564"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44